flares.note: This flare originates from beyond the east limb as seen from SDO AIA imagery and is likely occulted. Active Region 14341 was numbered on 2026-01-14.

cmes.note: CME observed to the SE in STEREO A COR2, also observed to the S in SOHO LASCO C3 following a data gap ending at 2026-01-09T04:22Z and in GOES CCOR-1 heavily obscured by the pylon. No distinct source for this CME is observed, but is likely outflow following large CME 2026-01-08T17:00Z from Active Region 14334 (S19E03) and a large dimming region to its south. SWPC_CAT triangulation corroborates this on-disk source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3.

cmes.note: CME observed to the SE in STEREO A COR2, also observed to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 following a data gap ending for LASCO C2 at 2026-01-09T04:17Z and in GOES CCOR-1 heavily obscured by the pylon. No distinct source for this CME is observed, but is likely outflow following large CME 2026-01-08T17:00Z from Active Region 14334 (S19E03) and a large dimming region to its south. SWPC_CAT triangulation corroborates this on-disk source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: This narrow CME is faintly visible to the west in STEREO A COR2 imagery. It is not seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME, but based on lack of visibility in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 it is likely a far-sided event from Earth's perspective.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky parameters based on best fit using STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT. The longitude for STEREO A's plane-of-sky is roughly 141 degrees at the start time of the CME.

cmes.note: CME observed to the SE in STEREO A COR2, also observed to the S in LASCO C3 following a data gap ending at 2026-01-09T12:30Z and in GOES CCOR-1 heavily obscured by the pylon. The source is likely outflow following large CME 2026-01-08T17:00Z from Active Region 14334 (S19E03) and a large dimming region to its south, with some extra dimming observed centered around S60E20 in SDO AIA 193 starting around 2026-01-09T06:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: STEREO A COR2 only measurement due to SOHO data gap and GOES CCOR-1 pylon obstruction of the CME, using the observed source centered around S60E20 as a basis. As such the latitude and longitude could easily vary +-5 degrees either direction, but high confidence in being out of the ecliptic.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and southeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is not seen in GOES CCOR-1 as it is blocked by the pylon. The source may be related to faint dimming centered near S50E20 starting around 2026-01-09T14:30Z seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: A very faint narrow jet-like CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 difference imagery and possibly seen very faintly in one or two timestamps of STEREO A COR2 after the data gap (but very faintly). Too faint to discern the front in GOES CCOR-1 and C3. Source could be a minor movement of field line on SE limb seen in SDO AIA 171 seen ~2026-01-10T01:50Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very speculative analysis since the only possible (and extremely minor) source seems to be on/close/behind the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 but (a very uncertain) fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2 and one or two rather questionable timestamps of STEREO A COR2) produces a fit of ~70 deg of longitude.

cmes.note: Very slow, streamer blowout CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-10T16:12Z. This CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. There is no definitive source for this CME on the Earth-facing disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. SOHO LASCO C2 was not used as the CME moves more slowly in early frames.

cmes.note: Thin jet-like CME observed to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 and unseen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2026-01-10T14:53Z. The source is a complex eruption associated with a C2.1 flare (S16W04) from AR 14339 peaking at 2026-01-10T19:42Z observed in SDO AIA 131, observed as what is likely two bulk fronts as CME: 2026-01-10T20:36Z and CME: 2026-01-10T20:48Z. Following the flare, filament ejecta is observed in SDO AIA 304 traveling S/SW but appearing to mostly fall back onto the disk likely associated with this CME, and that is followed by dimming starting around 2026-01-10T19:57Z centered around S27W02 observed in SDO AIA 193 likely associated with CME: 2026-01-10T20:48Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Half width less than 10 degrees. Single spacecraft 3D analysis due to lack of COR2A imagery and CCOR-1 pylon obstruction, using the observed flare source S16W04 as a basis. However, observed deflection of the CME in SDO AIA imagery and the inability to triangulate with other coronagraphs makes this analysis speculative, and the latitude/longitude could easily range within +-10 degrees.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 and unseen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2026-01-10T14:53Z. The source is a complex eruption associated with a C2.1 flare (S16W04) from AR 14339 peaking at 2026-01-10T19:42Z observed in SDO AIA 131, observed as what is likely two bulk fronts as CME: 2026-01-10T20:36Z and CME: 2026-01-10T20:48Z. Following the flare, filament ejecta is observed in SDO AIA 304 traveling S/SW but appearing to mostly fall back onto the disk likely associated with CME: 2026-01-10T20:36Z, and that is followed by dimming starting around 2026-01-10T19:57Z centered around S27W02 observed in SDO AIA 193 likely associated with this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft 3D analysis due to lack of COR2A imagery and CCOR-1 pylon obstruction, using the observed dimming source S27W02 as a basis. However, observed deflection of the CME in SDO AIA imagery and the inability to triangulate with other coronagraphs makes this analysis speculative, and the latitude/longitude/half-width could easily range within +-5 degrees.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2026-01-10T14:53Z. The CME front appears to form within the LASCO C2 field-of-view rather than appear behind the occulting disk, as such the start time is this first visible frame. No distinct on-disk source is observed.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C3 only plane-of-sky due to unobserved source and no STEREO A COR2 to triangulate.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-11T01:25Z. This CME is also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. There is no obvious source for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, so it is most likely far-sided. The is some minor field line movement near/beyond the SE limb best seen in SDO AIA 193 starting as early as 2026-01-11T00:12Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement (Lon. -90) based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Narrow, jet-like CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2026-01-11T05:12Z. This CME is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASOC C3, GOES CCOR-1, and very faintly in STEREO A COR2. There is no definitive source for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, so the source is most likely far-sided. There is slow, broad field line movement, beyond the E limb for several hours prior to the start of this CME best seen in GOES SUVI 284, but it is most likely unrelated.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME visible to the east in GOES CCOR-1 and in running difference imagery in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in real-time. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 in real-time due to a data gap. The potential source may be an eruption with dimming near S10E50 starting around 2026-01-11T16:12Z, best seen in SDO AIA 193. This CME is quickly overtaken in the field of view by CME with ID 2026-01-11T22:45:00-CME-001.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the potential source location. Limited imagery was used for this measurement due to the CME's faintness.

cmes.note: CME seen to the east in GOES CCOR-1 and to the east in running difference imagery in real-time for SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is an M3.3 flare as seen on the east limb across all wavelengths of SDO/AIA imagery starting at 2026-01-11T21:53Z. Rapidly opening field lines and post-eruptive arcades are also visible. The potential source for this flare and CME may be AR 14321, possibly located around S10E115, which rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2025-12-31, and may be a region of interest seen in NSO/GONG data.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on potential source location using GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery in SWPC_CAT.
Shock measurement based on the potential source location, with adjustment to best fit the shock of the CME in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C3 imagery.

cmes.note: Faint, fast CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, overlapping heavily with CME 2026-01-11T22:45Z. Not visible in STEREO A COR2, either due to faintness of front or being directed behind the occulting disk. No discernable source is observed for this CME, but is likely outflow with continued field line movement in SDO AIA 171 following significant O-type CME 2026-01-11T22:45Z, which had a potential source of former AR 14321, possibly located around S10E115, which rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2025-12-31, and may be a region of interest seen in NSO/GONG data.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft analysis with SOHO LASCO C2/C3, using E115 as the source longitude as this CME is likely outflow from CME: 2026-01-11T22:45Z with E115 as its bulk. Longitude could easily vary +-10 degrees.

cmes.note: Faint, fast CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, overlapping heavily with CME 2026-01-11T22:45Z. Not visible in STEREO A COR2, either due to faintness of front or being directed behind the occulting disk. No discernable source is observed for this CME, but is likely outflow with continued field line movement in SDO AIA 171 following significant O-type CME 2026-01-11T22:45Z, which had a potential source of former AR 14321, possibly located around S10E115, which rotated off of the Earth-facing disk on 2025-12-31, and may be a region of interest seen in NSO/GONG data.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft analysis with SOHO LASCO C2/C3, using E115 as the source longitude as this CME is likely outflow from CME: 2026-01-11T22:45Z with E115 as its bulk. Longitude could easily vary +-10 degrees.

cmes.note: Bright, wide CME observed to the N in STEREO A COR2, NE in GOES CCOR-1, and NE in running difference imagery in real-time for SOHO LASCO C2/C3 (first observed as early as 2026-01-12T04:48Z, white light not available in real-time). The source is far-sided over the NE limb, first observed as wide, slow field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193 and filament ejecta in SDO AIA 304 starting around 2026-01-12T02:13Z. Post-eruptive arcades peeking over the NE limb also observed as early as 2026-01-12T07:30Z in GOES SUVI 195, with a brief SDO eclipse period from 2026-01-12T07:00Z-T08:00Z missing this observation.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Narrow CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-13T04:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This event is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This CME appears to be outflow linked to continued field line movement seen in SDO AIA 171 and 211 following M3.3 flare and resulting CME: 2026-01-11T22:45Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to source beyond the East limb and lack of STEREO A COR2 to triangulate.

cmes.note: Hazy CME first seen to the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-13T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is field line movement seen to the South in SDO AIA 211 beginning at approximately 2026-01-13T04:19Z. Some movement in a Southeastern filament is also visible in SDO AIA 304 in association with this field line movement, but it does not appear that any material left the disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint puff-like narrow outflow to the E with a small bright front in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This feature is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap.  There is no clear source for this CME/outflow feature.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement within SWPC_CAT using SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 due to an overnight data gap. The source appears to be a filament eruption best seen in GOES SUVI 304 beyond the northern limb starting around 2026-01-13T19:42Z. It is a far-sided eruption based on SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI imagery. The front of the CME appears faint in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 with a brief brighter core portion that lingers behind. This is likely due to the nature of the filament eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit based on the possible SHOCK of the CME (fainter front ahead of bulk material) using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. Longitude is estimated based on potential source location and best fit in available coronagraph imagery. Due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints, the parameters may be off by +/- 10 degrees.
Parameters based on best fit of potential BULK of CME. Tracking the brighter portion of the CME in available SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 difference imagery.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-14T02:24Z. This front is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1 and to the NNW in STEREO A COR2. This CME is most likely outflow following CME: 2026-01-13T21:00Z which was associated with a far-sided filament eruption. No additional source signatures have been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Very narrow, faint CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-14T05:00Z. The structure appears part was into the FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. CME is also seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is possibly related to a C9.6 class flare from an unnumbered region near/on the NE limb that peaked at 2026-01-14T03:50Z. The flare is best seen in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 131.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-14T08:24Z. This front is also seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and is only speculatively by STEREO A COR2 due to poor imagery quality. A speculative source for this CME is a very minor eruption from AR 14340 (N14E16) best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2026-01-14T06:18Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 as well as a possible source location.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-14T13:38Z. This CME is only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and does not extend beyond the FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. With low confidence, the source of this CME could be related to an eruption from an unnumbered region centered around N10E42 beginning around 2026-01-14T13:16Z. The eruption is associated with some brightening best seen in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2 only. Plane-of-sky measurement chosen due to source ambiguity.

cmes.note: Narrow CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-14T14:00Z, as well as by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is not clearly seen in GOES CCOR-1 or SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is a small eruption denoted by a small region of dimming and field line movement seen in SDO AIA 193 centered at approx. N20E35 which began around 2026-01-14T13:09Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Slow, wide, streamer blowout-like CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2026-01-14T17:12Z. This CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASOC C3 and to the SE in STEREO A COR2. It is also seen in GOES CCOR-1 but is partially obscured by the pylon. This CME experiences some northward deflection in later frames and speeds up after it reaches beyond the FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. While measurement indicates that this CME is front-sided, there is no definitive source on the Earth-facing disk. A couple of source candidates include some minor field line movement in the far south best seen in SDO AIA 171 beginning around 2026-01-14T13:00Z and an eruption from AR 14336 best seen in SDO AIA 171 beginning around 2026-01-14T16:00Z

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2). There are two possible sources on disk, however neither of these sources closely corresponds to the fit.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery in real-time due to a data gap starting at 2026-01-14T16:23Z. The source may be related to an eruption and C3.8 flare from Active Region 14340 (N15E05) starting around 2026-01-14T23:40Z as seen in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304 and GOES SUVI 131/171/195/284/304 imagery. Dimming is observed near the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 195 imagery. A subsequent EUV wave is observed traveling northwest of the eruption site. Noting that a coronal hole located southeast of Active Region 14340 may be responsible for northwestern deflection of this CME. The start of the CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph and after the data gap its front is very fuzzy/faint in COR2 coronagraph. The CME is also partially obscured by the pylon in STEREO LASCO C3.

cmeAnalyses.note: Final but somewhat approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by the location of the likely source (C-class flare in AR 14340 (N15E05)). The CME front is very fuzzy in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph, as most of its propagation is covered by a large daily data gap in STEREO A. The CME is also partially obscured by the pylon in STEREO LASCO C3.

Very preliminary measurement made with one coronagraph (SOHO LASCO) based on the source longitude. The measured parameters are speculative as this measurement relies on early imagery. Additionally, a triangulated measurement is not available due to a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: Complex-shaped, bright halo CME with multiple (up to 3) fronts and a wide faint shock. Seen to NNW in SOHO LASCO/GOES CCOR-1 and to the NW in STEREO A COR2. Far-sided high N latitude source is clearly indicated by significant movement of field line in SDO AIA 171 to the NW starting after 2026-01-15T01Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit of two main lobes of this complex-shaped CME in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2).

cmes.note: CME with a wide faint shock and narrow bright bulk to the NE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the N or NNE in STEREO A COR2. The initially bright bulk soon becomes faint after a couple of SOHO LASCO C2 timestamps. The source is likely the long two-pronged prominence seen to the NE in GOES SUVI 304 after ~7Z. The prominence is likely obscured in SDO AIA 304 in two bad (all dark) images.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis of this far-sided CME made with the fit in two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO). The source (filament eruption) is behind the NE limb.
SHOCK measurement based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-15T23:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This CME is not currently visible in STEREO A COR2 due to an ongoing data gap beginning at 2026-01-15T16:23Z. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304 centered at approximately N55W30 with liftoff beginning at approx. 2026-01-15T22:06Z. It appears a majority of this material fell back down, but some fully erupted.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3.
